COVID-19 Crisis¶

The world is still struggling with one of the most rapidly spreading pandemics. There are a lot of people who say that data is the best weapon we can use in this "Corona Fight."

Imagine that you are one of the best data scientists in your country. The president of your country asked you to analyze the COVID-19 patient-level data of South Korea and prepare your homeland for the next wave of the pandemic. You, as the lead data scientist of your country have to create and prove a plan of fighting the pandemics in your country by analyzing the provided data. You must get the most critical insights using learned data science techniques and present them to the lead of your country.

Background¶

Requirements¶

  • Perform data cleaning and feature engineering. Work with features - handle missing data if needed, use Pandas date APIs, create other additional features.
  • Perform exploratory data analysis. Describe the data with basic statistical parameters - mean, median, quantiles, etc. Use parameters that give you the most important statistical insights of the data. Grouping the data and analyzing the groups - using Pandas aggregate methods. Visualize the data - you can use line, scatter, histogram plots, density plots, regplots, etc.
  • Provide clear explanations in your notebook. Your explanations should inform the reader what you are trying to achieve, what results did you get, and what these results mean.
  • Present the project - the data, methods, and results.
  • Provide suggestions about how your analysis can be improved.

Bonus Challenges¶

As a data scientists you will spend significant amount of your time learning new things. Sometimes you will do that for fun, but most of the time you will have an urgent problem and you will need to quickly learn some new skill to be able to solve it. It is very important to gradually build this skill - it is extremely valuable for all data scientists. The bonus challenges are designed to simulate these types of situations. These challenges require you to do something that we haven't covered in the course yet. Instead of trying to do all of the bonus challenges, concentrate on just one or two and do them well. All of the bonus challenges are optional - no points will be deducted if you skip them.

  • Try dimensionality reduction algorithm (e.g. PCA, t-SNE, Autoencoder).
  • Try clustering your data.
  • Try a machine learning model to explain relationships between features and predict new values.
  • Try to use a statistical significance test.

Not to lose important data in Patient_info dataset, I am going to replace NaNs.

Patient_info columns 'sex', 'age', 'city', 'infected_by' NaNs are going to be replaced:

  • 'sex', 'city', 'age' - No Info*
  • 'age' by the median of the South Korea age
  • 'infected_by' by '0000000000'**

*/ No Info the best represents collected data. The hypothesis is that the data was collected wrongly or all factors weren't included. By writing in 'sex' column 'Other' the data and graphs are going to show that there was an option for that. To be not mistaken, 'No Info' was chosen as the best option in this dataset.

**/ The 'infected_by' includes keys. The first one starts from 1000000001. The missing values can be replaced by 0000000000 then. It is going to help with clustering in the following steps and the data is not going to be disorted.

In [7]:
patient_info['sex'].fillna('', inplace = True)
patient_info['age'].fillna('No Info', inplace = True)
patient_info['city'].fillna('No Info', inplace = True)
patient_info['infected_by'].fillna('0000000000', inplace = True)
patient_info['contact_number'].fillna(np.NaN, inplace = True)

The 'contact_number' column values are the object datatype. To change NaNs to 'contact_number' mean, the following steps has to be done:

In [10]:
patient_info['contact_number'].str.contains('-').sum()
Out[10]:
0

A short explanation: the 'contact_number' cleaning lead to '-' character detection. I replaced them by NaNs. Then, to keep data undistorted, I could not change NaNs by zeros. The zeros are present in this column, thus it means, that the patient knew that there was no contact with him/her. I came to conclusion to change NaNs by negative number because patient can not have a negative number of contacts. Then I can easily change object datatype to numeric. After that negative values change to 'contact_number' median. I chose median because one outlier disturbed the value of the mean and it was not representing data correctfully.

q75,q25 = np.percentile(patient_info.loc[:, 'contact_number'],[99, 1])
intr_qr = q75 - q25
 
max = q75+(1.5*intr_qr)
min = q25-(1.5*intr_qr)
 
patient_info.loc[patient_info['contact_number'] < min, 'contact_number'] = np.nan
patient_info.loc[patient_info['contact_number'] > max, 'contact_number'] = np.nan

COVID-19 Situation Worldwide:¶

Here I am using shapely files for visualisation of world map.

The explanation of the following steps:

Since the .shp file includes only the data of countries map, location and etc., it has to be combined with the data that shows some kind of information for that specific country, e.g. how many COVID-19 cases are in the country?

Basically, I am trying to combine two different datasets by the country name and visualize it.

As mentioned before, this section helps us to indetify how much clusters are cases dataset and how we can this information implement.

In [107]:
kmeans_kwargs = {  
        "init": "random",
        "n_init": 10,
        "max_iter": 300,
        "random_state": 42,
    }
   
# A list holds the SSE values for each k
sse = []  # sum of squared error (distances in our case)
for k in range(1, 8):  # we will try clustering data into range(1, 8) clusters
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, **kmeans_kwargs)  # initiates the k-means algorithm
  kmeans.fit(scaled_features)  # fits k-means on our scaled data
  sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)  # Sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.
In [108]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots()
plt.plot(range(1, 8), sse)
plt.xticks(range(1, 8))
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("SSE")

fig.set(facecolor='white')
plt.show()

    )

Conclusions¶

The analysis of South Korea COVID-19 pandemic leads me to these conclusions:

  • South Korea was able to control pandemic by using the right tools: testing, isolation, provided hospitals with needed healthcare instruments.
  • The most sensitive age group is the elders: the deceased case numbers are highest in this group.
  • The childrens are not susceptible for COVID-19
  • The working class age groups should be restricted or isolated for not getting the contact with other people. The work should be done remotelly.
  • The travelling should be restricted and the contact with the person who whas COVID-19 should be avoided by not-healthcare people.

These actions should be taken for stopping the pandemic in each country.

What else could be done?¶

The implementation of this project could have been led into more sophisticated research:

  • The COVID-19 spread prediction
  • More statistical analysis how one event affect the other
  • How goverment's decisions lead to COVID-19 pandemic situation control?
  • Would South Korea's plan for stopping the pandemic work in other country?
  • The calculations of cases each day per 10k people
  • ...

...and many more questions to answer!
